            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1436631550,
            "creation_date": 1436629550,
            "body": "<p>Your <code>ArrayList<\/code> is of generic type which inherits from <code>Node<\/code>, and not <code>Node<\/code>, but you add a <code>Node<\/code> to it, which might be the wrong type - that causes the compilation error, since this operation might be unsafe. (See explanation at the end of the answer)<\/p>\n\n<p>One way to handle it is to declare your <code>ArrayList<\/code> as <code>ArrayList&lt;Node&gt;<\/code>, instead of <code>ArrayList&lt;? extends Node&gt;<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Another option is to declare the <code>DAG<\/code> class as a generic class:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class DAG &lt;T extends Node&gt; { \n   ArrayList&lt;T&gt; nodes;\n   T root;\n\n   public DAG(T root) {\n      /...\n   }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>Why is it unsafe?<\/p>\n\n<p>Look at the following code:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public static class A { \n\n}\npublic static class B extends A { \n\n}\npublic static class C extends A { \n\n}\npublic static &lt;T extends A&gt; void foo(ArrayList&lt;T&gt; arr, A a) {\n    arr.add(a); //this fails at compilation\n\n}\npublic static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n    ArrayList&lt;B&gt; arr = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();\n    foo(arr, new C());\n    B b = arr.get(0);\n\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>If the addition would have been successful - you would get a run time error!<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 31358900,
            "question_id": 31358864,
            "last_edit_date": 1436631550
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d653841b48ef3b965eaa9c8ce2a5075d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 292903,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 595943,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/595943/habsq",
                "reputation": 1832,
                "display_name": "habsq"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1436634182,
            "creation_date": 1436634182,
            "body": "<p>You need to understand what <code>ArrayList&lt;? extends Node&gt;<\/code> means. It basically an ArrayList with element of a type that extends <code>Node<\/code>. That element can be <code>Node<\/code> or other types which inherit <code>Node<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Perhaps this is what you need:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>class A { \n\n}\n\nclass B extends A { \n\n}\n\nclass C extends A { \n\n}\n\n\nList&lt;T extends A&gt; nodes = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();\nB b = new B();\nC c = new C();\nnodes.add(b);\nnodes.add(c);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 31359627,
            "question_id": 31358864
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/dd7716033b812f4260c419612734ce1a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 164059,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 386587,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/386587/erk",
                "reputation": 1219,
                "display_name": "Erk"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1436635455,
            "creation_date": 1436635455,
            "body": "<p>In your example I would have done:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class DAG { \n    ArrayList&lt;Node&gt; nodes;\n    Node root;\n\n    public DAG(Node root) {\n        // ..\n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>That way <code>nodes<\/code> can contain objects of type <code>Node<\/code> and any types that inherit from <code>Node<\/code>.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 31359833,
            "question_id": 31358864
        }
